A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that election fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on polling day and remove citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present an identity card with a photo.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo IDs issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same was true with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of the electorate represented only 46% of the voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The attorney general of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisanness of the laws that have been voted on and see it as an obvious goal to influence results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 votes needed by the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to say for sure that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate Cancer Screening: Passing the Test or Not?
In fact, the PSA test would sometimes present incorrect results, with false negative results or false positives, which result in unnecessary medical interventions.
This makes men who are already reluctant to pass screening tests even more hesitant.
Passing the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two specialists.
In studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had a screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that we have between 30 and 40% more chance of having metastases if we are not detected.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once cancer has been detected.
There are some aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
We really need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his or her cancer, offering him or her options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and instead opting, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
They will be suggested to do active monitoring and if the disease progresses, they will be offered treatment.
Increasingly, precise criteria are being determined for deciding who should or should not be treated.
I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if you should pass it or not.
