The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model – our best, or “less worst” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it’s still not entirely certain if it’s the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly sure.
Suppose it's the Higgs, since the chances of making mistakes seem slim, and let's see what it's about.
There is, in this little world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In a corner there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other one there are the Bosons, a filthy band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for that principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons then split into two groups, according to Berkeley Laboratories' (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "particles of force", through which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that precise location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "inconvenience" arises an electromagnetic wave (of light, or of infrared, or of ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it must reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could wrinkle the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring in circumference! - to reach such energies.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to a refrigerator by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, tens) do not.
Now, what "can" all this research bring, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Moreover, there are many who are eager to be found, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and block some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ops!).
But no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Consequences
The repercussions of this research in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. All-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the laser at Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - initially was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not its original intention at all, now serves as an “eye” for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate end-of-life issue.
The debate must resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
In this vital area, however, much remains to be done.
The Duty tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. still lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that gnawed him had left him a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I turned seven," he said, half a fig-drawn, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Attached to an appetizing lunch, he agrees to be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who work around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"During our lives, we learn that a man pisses upright," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Going back to the child stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois hospice are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and suffocated.”
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I no longer have wishes in life,” she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she expects a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether it is physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
In the dying, we will agree to provide oral care to brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer have to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as we help patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow each other but do not resemble each other.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man savoring his last family gathering in the courtyard, neatly tucked into his pillows while being toasted in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois house arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in the nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that has caused many palliative care physicians to fear the passage of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing anything necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only ask to die because they do not receive the right care.
And at the same time, many oncologists struggle with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she abandoned arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she said she regretted that I stopped fighting.
But she told me I was done!
Not almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not complying with their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients would be reluctant to treatment for pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is the practice of falling asleep until the patient dies, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
