A Constitution at the Forceps in Egypt
This is another poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
As Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which grants it provisional full powers, it has decided to play its va-tout.
Taking everyone off the hook, he announced Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this House an additional two months to finish its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a provisional text, which has repeatedly amended what weakens institutional stability and leads to legal cheating.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "treat the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within two weeks.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote is the ultimatum of the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I keep the full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange mood that 85 members of this constituent assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had shut the door, believing they could not have asserted their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 replacement members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators have amused themselves that one of the day's only differences has been expressed around... the time of prayer, with some members of the committee believing that the Constituent Assembly's pendulum was ill-adjusted.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Subject of all attention, Article 2 ultimately remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," say the Liberals, who see it as a communication blow.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly in verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further aroused by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It is referred to as "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ed].
And the question may arise in the future to what extent civil judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the defence budget review will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as demanded by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticoid.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, no more articles echo the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comfort, and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has retained five great reasons to go to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places.
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptismal funds" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus' miracles: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was at this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Rue de la Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Anointing Stone and the tomb.
This is where the Christian centre of the world stands, the symbol of humanity’s salvation.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews: the Western Wall, which is the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave there small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of Masada Fortress, an ancient refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are found on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is not possible to visit all of them during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
Mainly exhibited are the paintings of the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of molds of the visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures of Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not drop below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come here to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by Tel Aviv’s old town, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who have come to take photo shoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk in the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, do not worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchanged in shekels (now 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes composed of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk the haughty air.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be given a treat.
Car rental varies from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
On average, admission to the museum costs 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visas were cancelled on 9 February 2011.
"Who has the language, Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are arguing about what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling “false” certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to make money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language will have to be validated, as well as knowledge of the history of Russia and of the legal foundations.
You will need to validate your Russian language skills to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or educational diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, People's Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take exams in every city in the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, respond the representatives of the immigration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a job, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, on the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a “journey” in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment each other for months without food and paper and will have to commute between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“At home they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are cheated, their passports are taken, and they do not receive the stipulated salary,” said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to make money in Russia say that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to make money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
“You feel diminished and diminished.”
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will only be aimed at migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no examination or official work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or Defend to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khouchkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
“Be quick, don’t let go and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration documents of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language exam certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Forged papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners didn’t take them for nothing: every migrant who thus hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: this will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper bottles”.
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the exam the first time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against the bearers of civilian weapons.
This is the response of the authorities to recent incidents: whether the shootings carried out at weddings or the killings organized by the Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining the gun permit by increasing it from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma’s committee on security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the gun law would be introduced at the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "closing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a recorded weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tightening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing into the black market.
According to them, you can find any weapon in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is provided through several channels.
The main canals are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking weapons commands
The first is "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by the Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons coming from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often been subjected to explosions.
"Certified versions indicate that some fires were purposely set off to hide the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, the arms manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition in the international market and are selling weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” says one expert.
One of the other black market sources is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a local production, sometimes handicrafts, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply,” adds the former soldier.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts have assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was formed in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there “due to the fault of employees whose work is related to weapons,” the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "clandestine looting".
A salesman and consultant at an armory who has asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will fetch the new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
“He transports it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers," he added.
"Like in a luxury shop"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered me to come to the Begovaya station where someone came to take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you have to come also saying, for example, "On the part of such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He gives them only to me because he knows I won't give them.
The new kids are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s as he prepared to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, he said, have not changed.
He was given a photo album with “everything you want.”
“I thought I was in a luxury shop,” the soldier recalls.
There is no secret for the buyer, Baranets explains, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don’t just buy, we go with the seller to the forest and set up a target.
“They let me shoot and when I’m convinced the gun is working well, we start negotiating,” the expert describes.
A shop from its sofa
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different purposes".
For this, we do not need any documents and no one to meet.
“You just have to have a precise amount of money,” the ad reads on the website “Buy a gun or a fight machine gun.”
Users leave their request and ask their questions.
Do we sell to minors?
"Without permission, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (spelling preserved).
"Buy TT. Moscow", writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has broadcast a huge network of fake sites and shovels people willing to buy combat weapons.
People rush on food like hungry wolves and then they find themselves mining coal in Siberia
Victor Baranets, observer and former soldier
