U.S.: Fast Food and Supermarket Employees on Strike
Nearly a quarter of American teenagers go through a cashier’s job at McDonald’s
In recent days, a wave of protests has mounted against the low salaries of Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave will grow larger or fade quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Along with the modest wage increases for basic workers at Walmart and in fast food chains, the organizers of the demonstrations want to get the creation of unions.
This sector is not yet covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, as a flood of millions of people seized America and sometimes sparked outbursts.
On that day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize strike pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores whose products are intended for the modest and middle-class consumers.
Walmart markets everything from diapers to hunting rifles to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid Walmart employees shop only at their place of work.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply due to the low salaries of its employees.
They also complain about difficult working conditions, for example the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
The participants of the "Black Friday" protests demanded a salary increase, they complained that the price of the medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $ 30 to 100 per month.
For the Walmart basic employee who earns $9.5 an hour, that's an amount he can't afford.
Scientists at the California University of Berkley show that if Walmart increased the average salary to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That’s 1.1% more than he currently spends.
If Walmart were to transfer the entire wage increase onto the shoulders of consumers, every run in the store would cost them an extra 46 cents.
They will spend only $12.39 more in a year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8am to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over this period 5000 items per second.
Its coffers have made a total of 100 million transactions for "Black Friday".
The company’s spokesman Dan Fogleman told the left-wing Huffington Post that at least “less than five” Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was just a “com operation among so many” on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
The protests continued this week in New York and also concerned Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not very appreciated, which is why they are not yet established) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s advertises selling billions of servings and after they don’t even give you sick leave and pay you the work you did honestly!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, the federal and New York minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast foods increase them over time, but by a little, on average, its core employees make up $8.90 an hour in New York.
No one touches less than them in this city.
For me, it’s inconceivable to live with that money in New York.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald’s after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald’s employees who complain about having to live on this salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the forum of the Wall Street Journal there are comments saying that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know what you are going to feed them.
Protesters who launched the movement Thursday at 6:30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and fast-food cooks be paid a minimum of $15 an hour, more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for unions to be established in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing union protesters with bullying or firing.
However, administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a union, grabbing fast food remains a difficult task, and for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary rotation of the staff.
They don't agree
Other tumultuous demonstrations were held near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the mid-day rally near McDonald’s in Times Square with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: “McDonald’s announces selling billions of portions and after they don’t even give you sick leave and pay you the work you did honestly!”
The protesters were backed by other prominent New York Democrats, including mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio who said that “we all need to support fast food workers so they get a fair salary and the economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times characterized the event as the most important event in the fast food industry in its history.
But only a few hundred people participated, not all of them were fast food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is difficult to say whether this spark of mass movement will make small ones.
“At the moment, we can only manage to fool the brain.”
Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, Google unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November we learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it emerged from the interview with the director of the interactive 3D technologies group at the Microsoft Cambridge laboratory, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has for the moment remained flat-screen pixels and sometimes touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead and guess the radical changes that will happen with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today sells without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future hold for us?
- Although Kinect has made physical interaction, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information entry has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance, for now, is not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on truly 3D imaging systems that work on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to take the computer world out of ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space around him.
Thus, we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And to begin with, let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s appreciated, but isn’t it overrated?
One cannot say that it is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of his actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to order the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought about gestures, not wide gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the camera, but by a bracelet worn in the hand that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can on to you?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or cannot do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be for example laser sensors, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
If you’re interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don’t you like about modern cameras?
Are they lacking resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we rely in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are quite good, this adds work to the designers of algorithms.
We must keep in mind the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond lab gave the sensor touch a steady processing delay of between 1 and 100 s, with the current sensors closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device of this type in my work, but not needing to touch, to have more frames per second.
But shouldn’t the number of cameras be increased?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a usual sensor of the visible field.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem.
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, to play with the curve of the cameras and see how it could help define the locations.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not introduce its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most prospective platforms?
- Of course, walking all the time with a smartphone with your hands up is not practical but here is what I think: the best option would be a "transitory" augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch from glasses to smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and that is what makes them strong (personal items are the only ones you see) and at the same time their weakness: augmented reality from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem on which opponents of this idea point the finger: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth might very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
For the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image carrier.
It perfectly captures the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are actually intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example the interference of several ultrasound rays directed towards a precise point where the finger is and which gives you the sensation, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also an axis of work presenting perspectives.
- And you tried to trick the brain?
Make him believe that he feels what he should normally feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
There’s still a task down there that will have to be done for a long time: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that he is walking in an almost infinite open space – we are working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only manage to deceive the brain, there are still many years of work.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting to the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
