Birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Climate warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with Earthlings on board set out in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how to continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
“This is Venus and Mars,” says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If the conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the surface temperature of Venus is 500.
You can only live there at very high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to take an interest in the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from Earth varieties.
Then, insects were put into orbit, small drosophilic breeding flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
A completely normal chick is obtained at the exit.
Then the problems begin.
“The problem is that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its legs and start moving,” says Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
Finding no support, the chicks agitated in a disorderly way.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks reacted neither to the light nor to the sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We scoured their eyes twice, then gave up, because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological miniature ark with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only ship species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about the biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is still not possible to perform reproductions directly in space.
It's not a small deal.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike beasts, man is capable of doing so, in principle.
Homo sapiens has abstract thinking, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the robbery.
“No one answered that question,” says Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a retired rocket and space worker.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The father of the child, Andrian Nikolayev was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after having been twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicle environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it poses a danger even during flights in orbit," concludes pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must look for new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train at extra-vehicle exits.
The water imitates the weightlessness.
If for adults, the water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their real element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby evolves about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid in his mother's belly, it is easier for him to get used to the water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from its birth to its first bath, it only takes 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born the weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
You can of course prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will get to get him out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to ask to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the earth’s attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscle system.
You can't dress an infant like an adult with a special combination for training.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case, imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will result in the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely disabled," said Igor Pestov, director of the Committee for Bioethics at the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
The birth of children in space is still theoretical.
However, in time this will become a reality, when the Earthlings will travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born offspring.
The head of the ISC (Higher Institution for the Control of Public Finances) said: “the control of pseudo-self-employment (in Czech “Svarc system”) has failed because of politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but is lagging behind when it comes to its application.
This is what Miloslav Kala, the vice president of the Higher Institution of Public Finance Control, said in an interview with Aktualn.cz.
“The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking in us,” Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of the "varc system" by Petr Neșas.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG is not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls, so is it permissible or prohibited?
“The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits anything, even the head of government cannot prevent an inspecting authority from acting to demand compliance with the law,” Kala said.
At the control committee meeting in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German project in which the procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was it really about?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation, as well as a proper practice.
We have put all this together and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more stringent and of better quality", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This therefore confirms that it is not enough to continuously elaborate increasingly detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote oneself to the application of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it mean for you?
This kind of joint control should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering the market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those looking for its faults will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal issues concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there an institution similar to our CSI or a different mode of organization?
As for the institutions, similarly to the CIS, there is a similarly organised Bundesbildungshof, which also has a slightly different board, but these two institutions are basically similar.
The competences are also, to some extent, similar, but with a nuance compared to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it also has these types of account prices at the level of the different Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities are there controlled at the level of the Länder’s accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model but it certainly cannot be said to do better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better inspectors?
No, probably not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we consider to be a model, is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment of the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution, are its effects already being felt?
Since this amendment came into force relatively recently, it has not yet had an impact on our control operations.
As we do a posteriori checks, we must count on a certain delay.
Our comments concern only, for the moment, the process of preparing future controls - we have launched a new "mismanagement risk detection" instrument with which we have screened nearly 14,000 public contracts - that will of course be the case, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions of certain types of tender procedures and so on.
So do you see the passage of this law as an advantage or an added burden to the administration?
I believe that this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm this.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and that it is not possible to abide by them.
Already under the previous regulation, the claimant (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programs) forced the controlled parties to accept that any violation of the law on the markets meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really helpful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequences on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the way out?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDG was not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called ?varc system - what does that mean?
Is the VARC system prohibited or authorized?
The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demand compliance with the law.
He can say, “We’re going to change the law and allow it,” but he can’t say that we’re going to act like nothing is wrong.
The Markets Act contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be performed, precisely in order to protect the call for tenders.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and that is, in my opinion, what we lack.
