Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this agency, it is the second Member State of the former Eastern Bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, passionate Poles were working on spaceflights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture by A. Aternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The development of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later, Aternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Aternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The so-called Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a major propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the moon's hidden face.
In 1925 a draught was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only known information about this draught is that of the press at the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The records show that this research has reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by engineer Rohozi?ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were for military use with rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitee Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is talk of a company in the November 1954 issue of Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and by autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-story RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is still worth mentioning the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has raised a lively debate in the public opinion.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems geared towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This concretely means that the various economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and the (unlimited) free movement of private capital coupled with unbridled financial speculation.
Significant differences in the price of labour (wages) create a strain on prices.
It should be understood that a producer strives by importing low-priced goods to withstand economic competition by "making" the competitor's price more expensive, in order to take a greater share of the market and thereby increase his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, or buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social charges of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of the gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital generate in different economies a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically compel its own population to accept the price dictation of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is due on the one hand to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between rich and poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such salaries that the state is forced to pay a supplement to reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with salaries of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day their private country will invest in them.
The question here is: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; that capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, to get tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is therefore necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence and even govern today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and thereby the entire state.
The answer to that question is undoubtedly yes.
The evidence is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby that is present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, in the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that due to a lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of draft laws to law firms closely related to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that democracies oriented towards liberalism are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his work entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire at the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state was long ago in disrepair and the functions were assigned by violence.
Bribery, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-the-table and the corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with absolute votes already sold. ... ... “Honest people did not seek to obtain office, the result was once the state remained 8 months without consuls.” ... ‘ We really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was autocracy, and that we had to choose a true man.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard to the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result is, today as before, an unprecedented decadence of the elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
As things now stand, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal-style democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today’s elites are completely ignorant of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally, the Czech government will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
