The Argo movie: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a mob of protesters composed of Islamist students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had been supporting his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, in fact it could not abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The abducted diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After difficult journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rocky cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make snippets for the shooting of a great sci-fi movie.
Combination of genres
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
Details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful stroke, a treachery - as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow one another: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting has ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to be content with a subject offering in fact few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It does very well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at the airport in Tehran is dismissed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway are quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, by far, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the direction and retro style of the 70s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the portrayal of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the job.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a public inquiry into the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the settlement contest or ideas from the most absurd “EU workshop”.
“The fact that the EU has recently been considering adopting a 40 percent quota of women for the management of major European companies has led to our decision,” said the organiser of the survey, Patrik Nacher.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have benefited from life insurance rates because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations is, for example, the obligation to add bio components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to an increase in prices.
Criticism has also been levelled in the past against a de facto ban on the use of the term "strawberry" or the withdrawal from the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (so the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, at the root of the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonizing non-homogeneous national standards that made trade more difficult.
Fruit and vegetable standards have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, claiming that existing directives result in food waste.
The first prize can be awarded in this survey to last year’s EU regulation that should feature on inflatable balloons a warning that children under 8 should not swell without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a U.S. survey that balloons are among toys the leading cause of choking deaths of children.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing in fair trumpets.
We have weird ideas here, too.
The following rule concerning the European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme for Greece, anyone with an official function within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez-Fare" of liberal economists, the Bankovnípoplatky.com server named in this investigation, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food stocks that could be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and risked a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found the idea of paying money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting grants to apply for grants interesting.
These ideas, however, did not originate from Brussels but from Prague.
“The fact that we don’t have a sea handicaps us.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund," said Jaroslav Palas, Minister of Agriculture at the time.
He argued that because of our wheat production, and because of the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the State had found itself with full stocks that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech demand and organised a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
The grants for grants were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development led by Minister Pavel Näämec (US-DEU), which were, in practice, to be used to draft grant applications granted by Brussels.
The EU declares: "Odd regulations are rare".
While regulations are often criticised in Member States, many experts say, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the EU's functioning and overall development deserve praise.
More serious, for example, is, according to experts, the problem of using EU subsidies for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which have been imposed by the Member States during budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, must fight in Brussels for the right to use specific denominations for these traditional products (from which it does not always come out victorious) arouses strong emotions among the Czechs.
If at the end of six years of battle against the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvar?ky", as for the name "Tuzemsk? rum" that goes back to us in the nineteenth century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, and not on beet sugar, may bear the name rum.
In the official list of EU registered products, today we find together with world-renowned cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola ("Marzipan of Lübeck or Parma ham), cookies of Karlovy Vary ("Karlovarské sucary"), carp of Poho-elice and T-ebo-Po.
Pardubice Spice Bread ("Pardubick's perník") and cakes called "Ho'ice's Cornets" ("ho'ické trubi'ky") can also be proud of their community mark.
People want me to save the Republic, but I’m just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how do you come up with the idea of running for president?
It's not being a senator or a president that matters to me.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I wouldn’t be a candidate anywhere.
But I can no longer stand to see how the country has been looted for the past twenty years, that thieves are not under lockdown and taxes and retirement age are rising.
I didn’t have the ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I don’t like, then I try to come up with a solution to make it change.
And since I am over forty years old and I am an independent member of no party, I have no other way to influence the situation than to run for office in the presidential or senatorial elections.
You entered the Senate but quickly set out for the Château (N.d.T.: seat of the presidency).
Do you not turn your back on those who elected you?
I've always said that I'll start the battle for the Castle according to the results of the Senate election.
Later, I made it clear that if I were elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not function, it is only an instrument that allows me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the widest mandate.
The problem is not only that we as a nation are laughing at the bar or in front of our TV set, but also that we are trampling on those who are trying to make change.
Added to this is the press that breaks people’s reputations and confuses freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, I have been told that I bribe journalists or that I was the adviser to Ji? Paroubek.
Let's come to your visions.
You have started the fight for the Castle with as a battlehorse the themes of the material and criminal responsibility of politicians and retroactive tax declarations beyond twenty million [of CZK].
You have to change the law to that end.
As president, you do not have such power and only the Senate as a whole can propose legislation.
How do you solve this problem?
When I, as a citizen, pressed for tourism guide activities to be a liberal profession, I won.
The problem is politics: when someone arrives from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly rejected and it delays the citizens.
As an independent member of no party, I am much more likely to get the support of all parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without categorization and dogma supporters, to take from each side the best for our country and implement it.
Do you see yourself as a man of the right or the left?
From a Czech point of view, I feel like people are putting me on the left.
For me, whether it’s a little left or right, it’s not really important.
The important thing for me is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not that people are on the left or the right, but to bring people together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or the SDGs and I act equally impartially against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone says you are a populist?
But does not what you said prove it?
When you develop a business plan in a company, you also have a certain optimal purpose and vision.
You're trying to get closer to it.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I’m talking about have been applied by the world and recognized experts have talked about it.
But without the support of parliament, you only have slogans left.
You won’t survive long in politics with that.
Do you think that if you go to people and talk to them, you will succeed, for example, in imposing material and criminal responsibility?
I have no other choice.
I have to convince politicians, journalists and public opinion and try to rally them to my side in order to impose it.
If I were elected president, it would not be a problem to broadcast live on television my request to the presidents of parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal responsibility of politicians, officials, judges and prosecutors.
Maybe they should explain why they don’t want it.
When there is a strong personality who will identify the abuses, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take for example the election of the president by direct vote, it was obtained thanks to the pressure of public opinion.
I confess, without hesitation, to be an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and visions.
I’ve just gotten into politics and I’m trying to get the majority’s support for my program.
I'm trying to move things forward on my own, and if it doesn't work out, I'll stop in six years and go back to the private sector.
It's kind of like Okamura was supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that one person can't make a difference, which is why I went to a number of personalities to ask them to run in the Senate as well.
I met Radim Janura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
I at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencová who revealed the oil frauds.
I introduced myself because people are really unhappy but now I hesitate.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and what they did did, for the most part, gave their voice to a representative of the establishment.
In the Senate, we are two independents.
People have elected a Senate that can hardly impose change.
Nevertheless, I will fight for my vision, for example the direct election of mayors and prefects of regions.
Are you planning to start your own party?
No, not yet, because I don't have time to check if each potential member's past is spotless and then I don't have the financial means.
I also don’t have money for my presidential campaign, I only have twenty thousand on my “transparent” account.
You don't have any money?
You're talking about tax returns, what's yours?
I estimate the value of my personal property at about 60 million.
I have in Prague a piece of land worth 25 million, an apartment worth ten million, another apartment worth eight million, a collection of works of art worth about ten million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Skoda Superb worth 1 million and a few million on my account.
By the way, I own an Aston Martin, because it was a kid’s dream: I’ve always loved James Bond, who was riding in a car, being gallant with women and fighting evil and abuse.
You ride in Aston Martin, you have a fortune worth $60 million and you don't have money for your campaign?
You want to change the Republic but you don’t want to invest your own money in it?
It's not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for this campaign.
Should I be in debt?
I've already invested 2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors shows that my program does not attract much interest.
I don't have to pay for this campaign out of my pocket.
My campaign costs are generally covered by the remuneration I will receive as a senator.
But I couldn’t live on it, for example paying for my son’s English school, which costs 30,000 a month.
If my only goal was to make money, I won't run for election.
Are you going to continue your business activities in order to live?
Didn't you say you'd put your activities under control?
But this is not related to the amount of this remuneration.
As I promised, I partially cut back on my activities.
For example, my assistant will take over the management of the travel agency in the spring.
People would like me to be a Samaritan who saves the Republic.
But I have to live on something.
What was your usual monthly salary when you were an entrepreneur?
I was winning and I continue to win between two hundred and four hundred thousand.
If I were president, I would end my business.
