The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince themselves, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
“I think this building is funny, it’s very futuristic, finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, this building is indeed beautiful."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one is willing to go to one of these lame libraries anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a fairly special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get hold of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the Rotterdam architects' office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and ran for the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a laugh on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, the brash Maas stacked his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and adjoining houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of haughty ugliness, whose white facades invite us to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched with contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
Admittedly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you step on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library shelves are along the façade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” Maas says.
We have completely disrupted the classic spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been aptly designed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
Of particular beauty lies in the black beams of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair railings.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
So one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a frizzy farm.
In the Netherlands, one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It is cheap and we save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to the maintenance of the ideal level of air humidity of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun only lights up the interior for a short time, even on good weather days.
Thick wooden beams mounted crosswise with respect to the glass façade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambiance is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “finally found soul.”
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library that was not yet fully filled (now it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, “there is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
She may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians’ request to obtain observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not overly critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so-called defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are fighting on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the path to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean to Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and abstention from the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, as it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Maybe even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
However, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic American political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, of course, the government cannot defend its position publicly.
I believe that the true differences of opinion are not so great as they always appear to be.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Is Germany having difficulty reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think that makes it easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore form part of a larger political line and must assert their singular position.
This is what they are currently doing on the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will in the future take on the role of locomotive and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
This question has always been a tricky one.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany play a leading role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a bigger role.
If you look, for example, at the euro crisis, you notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn’t make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with very varied neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is only diminishing, but right now, the EU is not filling this void, so who remains?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don’t like it, even if they don’t like it and they are less appreciated, it’s life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America analyze together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
'Mark Protection' in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd win.
“It’s increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a workbook in which the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office are located.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by taking over part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeits.
Pattloch’s cases, however, are different: his constituents charge him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially gives Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that are designated women who marry rich men.
Chinese officials say they have nothing to blame.
