But here we are in the deep south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
This is where the Caucasian ethnic group named Talysh lives, about which little is known except that they speak Persian and Azeri perfectly and have very longevity.
Terminus: Lerik.
The small town plasteres with its overly aggressive architecture from the Soviet era that does not accord at all with the picturesque mountain scenery.
European tourists are rare here, the journey from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is far too difficult.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers, because the road has only one path.
The province has yet to take advantage of the legendary wealth that the country owes to its oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.
However, 48-year-old Pilata Fatulayeva is convinced that Lerik has the potential to become a tourist spot.
“Bakou became famous in May thanks to the Eurovision Song Contest, and next year there will be the oldest people’s festival in the world here,” says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, the only museum of its kind in the world.
There you can discover the life of about eight dozen Talysh of the region that are over 100 years old. Fatulayeva shows us a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather, he has reached the age of 120.
Having a child at 136
But the museum’s controversial star is irali Müslümov, a 168-year-old shepherd.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And when one thinks that the oldest documented person was 122 years old, Müslümov’s age seems more than doubtful.
“He was born in 1805 in this region, he died in 1973,” Fatulayeva said.
The man would have married three times and he would have had 23 children. At the age of 136, he would still have conceived a daughter.
Would it have been a mistake of a few decades to calculate his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max-Planck Institute in Rostock, also heard from him about the elderly man from Central Asia.
“Surprisingly elderly people also live in parts of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan,” Scholz says, “in Sardinia too, there are men who live incredibly old.”
However, it is impossible to establish scientific evidence due to the non-existence of the documents, besides the fact that there was no registry of civil status.
