Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of abuse that Bradley Manning allegedly suffered during the detention.
The trial involves Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history -- has missed many occasions to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein said that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring Manning's dismissal on the grounds that the seizure was under very difficult conditions and was sufficiently severe punishment -- occurred one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
During Friday’s hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein recalled the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards gave him was “excellent” and that the treatment he had received in the prison was overall “very professional.”
The forms did not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about some issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and yet it didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
Military Justice Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicide thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for his own protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to be removed from that status... so I could have a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered committing suicide when he was in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept abreast of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the regulations.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he had to drop his blanket that could have concealed his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is convicted before a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the least serious crimes and fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include theft of public goods or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defense information.
If all charges are brought, he will be sentenced to life in prison.
