The hardest job in the world: the human mules by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make their living carrying sulphur from Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh in total about 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, at a turtle’s pace, keeping their balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed deadly into Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers until the balance that a mining company has installed a little below 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, you could say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even used to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually travels three times a day.
It takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what he would gain in the fields.
“Miners’ income is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the porter who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not so difficult, but Anto returned to her family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I converted her to Java."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Misled by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wood mast with other bearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning as the sulphur does not cease to sprout at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater lighting up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not receive a sub of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) increase per camera, in addition to the entry of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for the beasts, not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
