A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, lengthens maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its leaders’ conservatism and strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, according to its national population distribution, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policies at the National Population Division, says it’s due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“It has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family formation,” she says.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and to delay marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counteract population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party last year had its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the drop in the birth rate has known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent the construction of many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger housing units.
They are more popular, in the sense that these homes are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our cash.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center, it seems that they are not going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, and so is education, which is why people postpone it,” says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
“But for me, it’s important to be able to have my money and my time,” another 20-year-old told us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons preventing them from having children.
So, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the final say.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Spanish Royal Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of private life that we can protect from intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under 16?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriodico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level and "the password and username" when they applied it to social networks.
“I’m not going to reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” Jorge, 10, says when trying to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
