On FB, I post cool images or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I’m not going to share one of my photos or someone who would do the stupid thing,” he says.
The boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine Twitter followers.
The majority are family.
Her mother is part of it, she knows the password to one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just post them,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly,” he says.
He said he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Nor will he trust someone who would recommend a stranger to him.
The case of José, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people on his list of friends.
“It doesn’t bother me because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to the boy, no one made any advances or asked him for his address or phone number.
“If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account,” he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A close friend of mine was sacked on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He only went privately."
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or angry.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key Issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, we must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information, but with the emergence of these sites, the rule of the game has changed," she said.
Porras reports that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master’s degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book “Natives and Digital Immigrants,” uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are the ones who are born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we are learning ourselves,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what it is appropriate to disclose, publish or say at an age where they do not have the maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she added.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach privacy to children and adolescents is to use questions that make them think.
“Their saying not to do it is useless,” she says.
Next, Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to post a picture of you like that of a friend you posted?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify party photos, do you ask others for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you’re doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
“Outside the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social media,” she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary teacher and education advisor, says it is essential that parents read the terms of use of social networks carefully.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation for discussing with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to share or publish,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven proxies present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be leaked after the summit closed, then claimed that it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among journalists was that given by press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who were attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the summit’s “final statement,” but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although it had been requested by the press, it had also not issued the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the ASPA official website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the collection of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment from the Hague Court that cuts a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima filed against Santiago and that begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we bring to this international court today,” said President Humala.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals,” Piñera said in a statement.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
He read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would set up "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and envision a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” he said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a ICJ judgement requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will review all these routes, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with this country,” he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the seizure of power of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, in the context of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although UNASUR is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
