AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the test result: HIV-positive.
“It’s as if the sky had fallen on my head,” he said, referring to the moment of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make “less painful,” in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it and his hardship was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye “because he was speechless.”
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, “exhausted” their immune system and become victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as reference that this scientific information was validated in April of this year in.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depended on the level of immune system involvement that patients presented at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not consume drugs.4
To put it simply, it means that for someone who would be diagnosed with HIV-positive at 25, “as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” the scientist said.
In order to put this progress back into context, it is important to know that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
While mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual UNAIDS report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there have been 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don’t think the problem is with access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
In the last 12 years at least, we have never lacked drugs, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
He gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we need to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all people who ask for it".
The specialists and members of the State AIDS Prevention Council of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and despite his young age, he was already an AIDS carrier and suffered from Kaposi sarcoma.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
“If I’m going to die, I’d better have sex three times a week,” they say.
The change was beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and to the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his privacy with Milenio Jalisco to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
That they do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible for it.
His message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs of a hundred, it's very good, but it results, that even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question, "What are you going to do with it?", sarcastically asked by social workers, counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers don't want to hear.
It proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at the counters, but also be found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"This is not how sexuality works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active," he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The State is the 4th state in the number of new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are bloodborne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know about it.
A U.S. court-approved judgment ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a detrimental precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighboring country and solvency issues.
Therefore, it seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star flag, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, Judge Harlin Hale’s June 15 ruling on the Northern Texas Bankruptcy Court leaves Mexican companies defenseless of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s leading glass maker to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the case judge points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, sitting in New Orleans, claims that the main proceeding is commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognized in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the case of Vitro is not the first to use this plan.
Here are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, which the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcies had secured debts.
