The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae (“friend of the Court”) detailing Vitro’s proceedings under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, noting that this freed him from agreements signed by both countries to level it up with paragraph 15 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he noted that the country had adhered to the United Nations Commission on International Trade principles, i.e. rules for cross-border insolvency, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
